Pages = {283-288},
Abstract = {The Euphorbieae and Hippomaneae, though both usually placed in subfamily
   Euphorbioideae, differ in many inflorescence details and can be linked
   unambiguously only by one cryptic character: the rod-shaped starch
   grains in the latex. While the Hippomaneae have inflorescences very
   similar to those of many other members of the Euphorbiaceae, the
   Euphorbieae have an inflorescence so specialized that one seems to be
   forced to relate it to other members of the family througb a
   hypothetical ancestor with a synflorescence of axillary bisexual cymes
   more primitive than most extant taxa possiblv other thari Jatropha.},
